            <h1>beava</h1>

            <h2 id="fresh-state">Fresh state without a streaming platform</h2>
            <p className="bv-lede">beava is a single-threaded event processing and serving engine for building real-time features with much less infrastructure.</p>
            <p>It lets developers define streams, feature tables, aggregations, and windows in a declarative Python SDK that feels closer to Polars than traditional stream processing frameworks. Events can be pushed over TCP or HTTP, and fresh features can be served immediately through simple <code>get</code> and <code>mget</code> queries.</p>
            <p><strong>beava turns events into fresh, queryable state.</strong></p>
            <p>The goal is to make real-time feature pipelines feel as lightweight, practical, and straightforward as Redis.</p>

            <h2 id="why">Why beava?</h2>
            <p>Modern applications need to make fast decisions from recent data. Models rank, personalize, predict, bid, route, and react in milliseconds. Agents increasingly need fresh state about users, tools, products, workflows, and the environment around them.</p>
            <p>But developers still lack a simple way to process the latest event data and query it immediately.</p>
            <p>The standard stack often becomes a collection of separate systems: an event bus, a stream processor, a serving store, and custom glue code. That stack is powerful, but for many application teams it is too heavy, too slow to adapt, and too far away from the code developers want to write.</p>
            <p><strong>Stream processing should not require a platform team.</strong></p>
            <p>beava exists because teams need a simpler primitive for turning events into fresh, queryable, windowed features and agentic state.</p>
            <p><a href="/docs/vision/why-beava/" style={{color:'var(--accent)', fontWeight:600}}>Read the longer story →</a></p>

            <h2 id="how">How beava works</h2>
            <p>A beava app has three basic parts:</p>
            <ol>
              <li><strong>Streams</strong> describe the events your application produces.</li>
              <li><strong>Tables</strong> describe the grouped, windowed, aggregated state you want to maintain.</li>
              <li><strong>Queries</strong> let your application fetch the latest values by key with <code>get</code> and <code>mget</code>.</li>
            </ol>
            <p>As events arrive, beava updates the relevant tables inline and makes the latest values available to your application.</p>
            <p><strong>Low-latency reads are useful; low-latency freshness changes the architecture.</strong></p>
            <p>When a new event becomes queryable quickly enough, teams can put fresh state directly inside personalization, ranking, bidding, fraud, recommendation, and agent decision paths.</p>

            <h2 id="build">What you can build</h2>
            <p>Use beava when <strong>fresh events need to become a fast decision</strong>.</p>
            <p>Common starting points include:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><strong>Personalization and recommendations</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Real-time bidding and ads systems</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Fraud, abuse, and risk scoring</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Agentic state</strong></li>
              <li><strong>Product analytics that become product logic</strong></li>
              <li><strong>ML feature iteration</strong></li>
            </ul>

            <h2 id="start">Start here</h2>
            <p>If you are new to beava, start with the quickstart:</p>
            <ul>
              <li><a href="/docs/get-started/quickstart/">Quickstart</a></li>
              <li><a href="/docs/get-started/define-a-pipeline/">Define a pipeline</a></li>
              <li><a href="/docs/get-started/push-events/">Push events</a></li>
              <li><a href="/docs/get-started/query-features/">Query features</a></li>
            </ul>
            <p>If you want to understand why beava exists, read:</p>
            <ul>
